BTM, 20th October 2016

What is R Markdown

  • Framework for creating dynamic documents, reports and presentations
  • A tool for integration of R-code execution results into your document

. . .

Why do we need it?

  • To ensure reproducibility of the results
  • To convert the .Rmd file into different formats
    • HTML
    • PDF
    • MS Word (ODT, RTF)
    • Markdown
    • Presentations: ioslides, reveal.js, Slidy, Beamer
    • Website templates
  • Easy to write and format your documents
  • To share open code, ideas, algotirhms and research results

Reproducible research and collaboration

  • Paper in "Nature": more than 70% of respondents can not reproduce their colleagues' results
  • And it gets worse:
    • More data
    • Complex data analysis schemes
    • Models and algorithms need a lot of fine tuning
    • Traditional journal paper format is not enough anymore
  • Ropensci reproducibility guide

An introduction to Rmarkdown: Inline code

  • Simplest stuff: insert the result as text inside a string
  • Syntaxis: backtick ("`") - "r" - space - R-code - backtick
  • Example: "The theorem is proven under the assumption pi equals `r ceiling(pi)`."
  • Result: "The theorem is proven under the assumption pi equals 4."

An introduction to Rmarkdown: Code chunks

  • The basic way to insert code
  • Every chunk can be tuned separately using options
  • Chunk may print something out, draw a plot or have no output

An introduction to Rmarkdown: Chunk syntaxis

```{r}
head(iris)
```

An introduction to Rmarkdown: Option echo=FALSE

  • You can put options for a chunk in figure brackets
  • By default both code and results are shown
  • Option echo=FALSE supresses printing the code:

. . .

```{r, echo=FALSE}
(1:10)^3
```

. . .

##  [1]    1    8   27   64  125  216  343  512  729 1000

An introduction to Rmarkdown: Layout

  • **Bold** __font__ –> Bold font
  • *Italic* _font_ –> Italic font
  • Monospeced text `sum(x)` –> sum(x)
  • Upper and lower indices A^2^~i~ –> A2i
  • ~~Strikeout~~ text –> Strikeout text
  • Symbols escape: \* \_ \\ \$ –> * _ \ $
  • Autocorrection of dash and long dash: -- --- –> – —

Main elements of Markdown

  • Headers: # Header 1 – ###### Header 6
  • Hyperlink: <https://www.github.com/nvolkova> –> https://www.github.com/nvolkova
  • Hyperlink in text: [My github](https://www.github.com/nvolkova) –> My github
  • http://www.rstudio.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/rmarkdown-cheatsheet-2.0.pdf

Latex support

  • To build a pdf you need to install \(\TeX\) (MiKTeX, TeX Live)
  • $\hat{\beta} = (X^T X)^{-1} X^T y$ –> \(\hat{\beta} = (X^T X)^{-1} X^T y\)
  • $$i \hbar \frac{\partial}{\partial t} ... $$ –> \[i \hbar \frac{\partial}{\partial t}\Psi(\mathbf{r},t) = \hat H \Psi(\mathbf{r},t)\]
  • It has all the functions available in \(\TeX\) (settings, packages, macros etc.)
  • Formulas are shown correctly in HTML thanks to MathJax

knitr

  • Tha package knitr processes Rmarkdown code
  • Can also be used independently from R Markdown
  • Initial focus of knitr – pdf (LaTeX + R)

Global options

  • Usually given in the beginning of a document
  • knitr::opts_chunk$set(echo=FALSE, fig.width=5, fig.height=5)
  • It's convenient to put it in a separate chunk with an option include=FALSE

Chunk options

  • There are several global knitr settings
  • Every chunk can have its own local settings that overwrite global
  • Local settings should be separated by comma
  • The list of settings can be foound on http://yihui.name/knitr/options/

Main options

  • echo (default: TRUE) – showing the sourcecode
  • eval (default: TRUE) – executing the chunk
  • include (default: TRUE) – showing the execution result
  • error (default: FALSE) – showing error text
  • message (default: TRUE) – showing message text
  • warning (default: TRUE) – showing warning text

Main options

  • comment (default: '##') – prefix to be set before every output string
  • results (default: 'markup') – output layout
  • highlight (default: TRUE) – highlighting code syntaxis
  • tidy (default: FALSE) – formatting (spaces and indents)

Chunk labels

  • You can put a label in the curved brackets between "r" and chunk options
  • Chunks can call each other by labels

. . .

```{r chunk1, echo=TRUE, results='hide'}
cos(2*pi)
```
```{r chunk2, echo=FALSE, ref.label='chunk1'}
```

. . .

cos(2*pi)
## [1] 1

Graphics

  • fig.height, fig.width – image size (in inches)
  • fig.align (default: 'center') – image position on the page
  • fig.cap (default: NULL) – string with image subtitle

. . .

Caching

  • Some chunks may contain lots of calculations
  • For those you'd like to put cache=TRUE
  • Cache only works when nothing inside a chunk has changed
  • NB: if your chunks are tied, remember about the cache!
  • In such cases you could use the function dependson
  • NB: some algorithms may use random number generators!

Getting started

  • Make sure you have installed the following if you haven’t already done so
    • R (https://cran.rstudio.com/)
    • Rstudio (https://www.rstudio.com/products/rstudio/download/)
  • Get into pairs

Getting started

  • Create a new Rmarkdown (Rmd) document
  • File → Newfile → R markdown…
  • Follow the prompt to install knitr (if it appears)
  • Set a title for your document
  • Enter your name in the author field and hit “OK”

Bonus exercise: generating slides

  • You can even generate nifty html slides with Rmarkdown
  • Just add “output: ioslides_presentation” to the header

. . .

---

author: "EMBL predocs"
date: October 20, 2016
output: ioslides_presentation
---
